anyone with multiple sclerosis have a motorcycle i always wanted another motorcyle cc range is this a good idea anymore now that i have been dx'd with multiple sclerosis months ago i have ms the only one who knows what a person with ms can do is the person who has it since no two cases are the same there are plenty of people with ms who live normal lives if you are not having balance problems short term memory problems optic neuritis or any other physical disability driving a motorcycle is not a problem go take the test you cannot put off living if you have ms on the basis of what the ms might do in the future i have friends with ms who para sail bungee jump and parachute if i don't feel well on a particular day i scale back my activities if i feel well i do whatever i want and that is what anybody who has this disease does go for it if you know you are capable and if your ms gets bad put it in storage and once you are feeling good again get it out of the mothballs and ride go have fun every chance you have you know how unpredictable this disease can be so live for the day Motor neurone disease Equine conformation Motorcycle Social rule Narcolepsy Chronic fatigue syndrome Autoimmune diseases Urinary incontinence Abortion debate Optic neuritis Traumatic brain injury Computer Alcoholics Anonymous Mach kernel Hypoglycemia Mental retardation Coeliac disease Stroke Fecal incontinence Tuberous sclerosis Normal distribution Nystagmus Central processing unit Disease Sport Sensory Integration Dysfunction Tank Parachute Non-Hodgkin's lymphoma Cephalic disorder Parachuting Psychosis Tocopherol Vitamin C Glossary of medical terms related to communications disorders Health insurance Human sexual behavior BMW USB flash drive Theory of conduct Carburetor Clinical depression Muscular Dystrophy Association Goodness and value theory Pregnancy DVD Spina bifida Androgen insensitivity syndrome The Ashlee Simpson Show K' Knight Rider Alignment (role-playing games) Optic nerve Prostate ca